msItem.title: Cath Fionntrágha
msItem.explicit: ... 7 do mharbadh nóchad fear leis ar gach cuart diu

msItem.title: 'Triallim siar go hEirinn áin'
msItem.explicit: ... { os } uime a tus aig triall. Triall

msItem.title: 'Mor anocht esbidh Finn'
msItem.explicit: ... ba righmhoir is ba romor.

msItem.title: 'S fada tangamur for thig'
msItem.explicit: ... tangamur fein go fada.

msItem.title: 'A laoch ud a togbis a ccenn'
msItem.incipit: A laoch ud a togbis a ccenn ...
msItem.explicit: ... gur dechtir gan ghabhail riut. A laoich.

msItem.title: 'Cenn madan dhelbh chasaich mic Duinne'
msItem.incipit: Cenn madan dhelbh chasaich mic Duinne ...
msItem.explicit: ... aig teisgart chorp agus chenn. Cenn.

msItem.title: 'Sgela leat a Thurinn thenn'
msItem.explicit: ... a Brain nach duit is drochsgeul.

msItem.title: 'Moisi a Brain mic Febhil'
msItem.explicit: ... Deirim riu is mochen. Mo.

msItem.title: 'Togibh ar croidhe le fianna Fail'
msItem.incipit: Togibh ar croidhe le fianna Fail ...
msItem.explicit: ... ar matha fer do nith sibh. Trogibh.

msItem.title: 'Éiribh suas a Thuath Dé'
msItem.explicit: ... Cumibh agus éiribh.

msItem.title: 'Feuchir liobh esib ar sluaid'
msItem.explicit: ... O chaidh sinn fein da féchain.

msItem.title: 'An innise a bhfuil sinn nocht'
msItem.incipit: An innise a bhfuil sinn nocht ...
msItem.explicit: ... A hainm ar an innis. An innise.

msItem.title: 'Do chraidh mo chrioidhe finn fhéile'
msItem.incipit: Do chraidh mo chrioidhe finn fhéile ...
msItem.explicit: ... sé s mo chraidhis mo chroidhe. Do chraidh.

msItem.title: 'Fas nocht treab Theamhra'
msItem.explicit: ... Temur go bronach bith fás. Fás.

msItem.title: 'Geltair gealtach gioll a sgeoil'
msItem.explicit: ... acht beith na gheltair geltach.

msItem.title: 'Comhric Dholuir ar an traig'
msItem.explicit: ... ba chosgirrach an comhrig.

msItem.title: 'Cenn mic Draguin mo duil'
msItem.explicit: ... aon fer do bhenadh dhe chenn. Cenn.

msItem.title: 'Eirich a righ Theamhra'
msItem.explicit: ... teid san catha cách. Éirich.

msItem.title: 'A Charbre na clód'
msItem.explicit: ... s tu an cara rom-char.

msItem.title: 'Falb anois a Chaomh-Chaolt'
msItem.explicit: ... s mairg da ndan a comhrig.

msItem.title: 'A mic Cubhill eirich'
msItem.explicit: ... bios orrderic dod macibh. A mic Cubill.

msItem.title: 'O shith Thadg thanig fhir'
msItem.explicit: ... acht des labraid on ardshith. O shith

msItem.title: 'A fhiannibh Fhinn thig a suinn'
msItem.incipit: A fhiannibh Fhinn thig a suinn ...
msItem.explicit: ... do Fhionn s da feinn. A fhiannib.

msItem.title: 'A maite na feine'
msItem.explicit: ... is uimid ar er morlaochibh.

msItem.title: 'Frithalimh Fóirne'
msItem.explicit: ... fiorduin sarcaraid. Frithalimh Fóirne.

msItem.title: 'Is adbill an griom sa'
msItem.explicit: ... s a nert fioradhbhal.

msItem.title: 'A Fiodaic anglonnich'
msItem.explicit: ... na ceil Fiodhaich.

msItem.title: 'A Conan chruaid'
msItem.explicit: ... tigerna con. A Conan.

msItem.title: 'Do cius cruthe milid'
msItem.explicit: ... rug buaidh mur do cíusa.

revisionDesc.change: Transcription by MMA, beginning on page 5

note.p: This word is formed out of a "g" with a suspension stroke and a lenition mark. This appears elsewhere in this MS. As the sound represented by the o in go can be represented by odh elsewhere, the present editor understands this as a generalised abbreviation to represent this sound even though go, historically, did not contain a d Nonetheless, in order to accurately represent what appears in the MS, the suspension stroke and lention dot have been expanded as odh here and elsewhere where the same appears.
The king of Fir Connachenn is named as Comhair cromchennach later in this text (p.14, l.2).
Ronald Black (0080846) has noted Foirnna as the brother of rí an Innia rather than the brother of rí Lochlann.

The same character's name appears with a median m, not a g in all other instances in this text where the name is written plene, or, where an abbreviation is only present to represent the final -(u)inn.
Black (0131203) has taken this as urra. A form of farrad, however, is better suited to the context.
For more on this term see Richard A.V. Cox (2008): §5 cnarra.
For more on this term see Richard A.V. Cox (2008): §3 carbh.

Black took sgiobhidh to be a form of sgioba, 'crew' (0120461), and tentatively took asguind as éasgaidh, 'nimble' (0021043). However, as this section describes the readying of the ships to set sail, and as the following phrase uses the same syntax to describe the preparation involved, this phrase appears to be best understood as consisting of the verbal noun sgiabadh, 'moving', the possessive a, and the genitive of the noun sgonn, '[block(s) of] wood'.
For more on this term see Richard A.V. Cox (2008): §7 sgoth.
Black made a very tentative translation of sirrginn as 'jerkin' (0120674). The noun seirrcenn, a type of boat, better fits the context.

Black (0061174) has noted the possibility that dis in this context may mean prow. In this edition dis has been understood as a form of días, referring to the wooden beams/planks of the ship. As a ship narrows todards it prow, the present editor postualtes that díslethan mayconsequently being understood as wide-hulled.
Black (0060936) appears to have understood the first element as a form of the adjective dag. The present editor has taken it to be a form of the noun dead.
Black understood this to be a compound of mearra (0101138), not attested in either DIL or Dwelly, and gríobhach (0090619). In the present edition it is understood to be a compound of mér and gnímach.
Unlike the present edition, Black took this to be a form of laimrigeach (0100063).

Black (0060409) understood this to be cruinneach, with the meaning given as 'ball-rounded'. It does, however, seem that a form of crithnaigthech, with the compound meaning 'making the ropes/rigging shake’ may be more appropriate given the power implied by the other preceding adjectives.
Black opined that if troitheadh 'is not error for srothadh, it is some word for the rough surface of the sea' (0130860). The present editor has understood this differently.
Black (0100540) took this to be a form of lìonadh, unlike this edition in which it is understood to be the plural of linn, pool.

Black suggested that this may be composed of possessive a and the genitive of ball (0030090). The syntax of the sentence would not support such a reading, however, and in the present edition it is understood to be a form of adbal.
Black has understood this compound somewhat differently, taking it as 'full-winded' (0090039).
Black posited that ropin may mean 'sheets' (0070665), although in this context a word for rope would make more sense.

Black (0020534) postulated that this compound may mean 'tricky-to-hoist'. The placement of a question mark after this interpretation, however, would appear to indicate that he was somewhat doubtful of this interpretation.
Black interpreted the word as being from Boillsgeanta (0080846), and meaning 'shining'. The present editor, however, is of the opinion that this is a form of basganta.
Black (0002839) has a single word and takes it as the dative plural of súgad, rather than a compound of súgh and inne as it is understood in the present edition.
Black understands this as taisdealach (0121124). An adjective derived from tustall, with a meaning of 'rushing' or 'quick-moving' would be more appropriate here.
Black (0120466) took this to be a form of cladh, with epenthetic vowel, and sgìth, whereas here it is understood to be a compound of clad and éscaid.
Black (0070695) gives this as a form of druim. In the present edition it is understood to be a form of drumman.

Black took this to mean do-fhreagartha (0070402), translated as 'unanswerable, matchless'. If fresgirra is taken to be participle of the verb do-scara/ trasgair, do-thrascartha can be understood as 'unconquerable' and is thus an apt descriptor of the sea.

Black provides the same reading as this transcription but did not provide a translation (0081048). The HDSG notes on the same word say that 'The exact reading of this word is uncertain [and] the meaning of it evades me' (0081048).
The brecht component could be from brecht, as above, or brecc as in Black's notes (0030741).

p.note: Black has interpreted gabh as part of a compound gabh thar, meaning 'to put on, assume' (0081088). In this passage, however, we get do ghabh a muir [..] a brat lethann [...] fairis, indicating that the sea covered the party, presumably meaning that a wave washed over the fleet.

note.p: Black took this to be a form of eagconnla (0070860). Here it is understood to be a form of écsamail.
Black took this to be a form of rànaich (0110903). Here it is understood to be related to bruthnaigidir.

Cecile O'Rahilly (1962): l.55, has caithem in this position Black (0031067) understood caichadh to be a form of caithem based on O'Rahilly's edition. If caichadh is understood as a form of cathadh, however, as it is in this edition, it would appear to mean that their words were lost to the wind due to its strength. This would chime well with the present editor’s interpretation of the rest of the sentence, namely that the wind is rendering all their actions ineffective.

Black (0002847) understood this as a form of suidhe. A form of sùdh, meaning the overlap of the planks in a clincher-built boat may be more appropriate given the destruction implied by the planks coming apart.

Both Black (0020109) and O'Rahilly (1962): l.63, have taken this as a form of adbar, meaning 'timber'. Another possibility is that it comes from ábur, meaning 'oar-hole'. As the latter is less frequently attested than the word adbar, the former is probably more likley.
Black (0070664) took this compound to mean 'sheet' but a compound word with rop, 'rope' as the second element is more likely.
Black (0081133) understood this as being a form of gàireach, not garg as in this transcription.
Black (0100905) understood this to be màthaireil. The present editor understand it to be a compound adjective formed from múit and réimmemail.
Unlike the present transcription, Black understood this a single word, maolann (0100981).

Black (0110723) thought should have been a form of uisce. In the present edition it is understood to be a form of airde, and the this section should be understood as 'airde [tuinne] no anafidh tuinne.'
It may be that the b at the beginning of this word is simply badly formed but it resembles surrounding forms of the letter l too closely too transcribe as b.

Of this form Black (0130915) says that 'This a rather amusing corruption. The original text (cf. O'Rahilly's ed. [(1962)] l. 102) has a ndubhchonn "chants". Alasdair has assimilated this to tùchan "cooing of a dove".'. The MS could, however, be simply representing dúchann, given other instances of other t/d alternations, e.g. p.7, l.27 dusa for (a)tú-sa.
The present transcriber understands this as the Early Gaelic cétóir. Black analysed it as two words, ceud (0040042) and úair (0130991), albeit with the same meaning as cétóir.

The characters here could be either 'comhchonirt' or 'comhchom[a]rt'. It does not make sense to understand it as -ni- as we are unlikely to see comh prefixed to "comhneart". That "comhcomairt" is in O'Rahilly (1962): l.127 also makes it more likely that Mac Mhaighstir Alasdair's exemplar had a version of comhchomart and that the vowel between the m and r has been omitted here.

This form appears to be a corruption or development of 'geosadánaibh sanaisi' in O'Rahilly (1962): l.152. The -imh ending, used elsewhere in this text as the dative plural ending, suggests that this was understood to be from a word "geós" or similar. The separation of geosimh and danuinn in the MS further the idea that "geosimh" is a word unto itself (due to the spacing generally employed in this MS). The genitive of Danann is easily understood to imply some sort of magical quality, whether employed to refer to the supernatural in the abstract or the Túatha Dé Danann specifically. One possibility is be that geòs may have been thought to be a form of the word geas meaning "charm, sorcery, enchantment." This would fit the context: "We will create a magical host around you from the supernatural charms/ charms of [the Túatha Dé] Danainn."

Black (0101006) has màireach as the headword here. Mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair also has the phrase written as three words ar na mhairich. This appears to indicate that the phrase has been re-analysed as a preposition, article, and noun.
Black (0002069) appears not to have known of the prefix abar/amar when writing this slip.
Black took this as a compound formed from lúth (0100696) and bechtach (0030220), unlike this transcription in which it is understood to be a compound from lúb and échtach
The form of the initial a here is unusual but it appears that Mac Mhaighstir Alasdair began writing an o then changed to writing an a. The character has thus been transcribed as an a here.

This transcription gives the linked headword as buileachadh in Dwelly. There, there are examples accompanied by the preposition air where the meaning is translated as 'bestow'. Black (0030894) also gives the headword as buileachadh with his translation being 'I give up to' and the HDSG translating this particular piece as 'his nature was compelling him to give himself up to C.C.' While the headword buileachadh does fit the context, there is other possibility if one looks to Dinneen, namely bailighim meaning 'conjoin, collect'. If one were to understand this as the verbal noun of bailighim the meaning of the sentence is clear: His nature was compelling him to unite himself/ally himself/team up with Conn Critir and the fían.

There is a suspension stroke above the o in domin that cannot sensibly be expanded. Mac Mhaighstir Alasdair frequently employs a colon in the same way as a suspentions stroke, i.e. the colon can abbreviate any character(s). It is therefore reasonable to understand the colon as standing for the -in at the end of the word, meaning that we have a full word with no missing components at this point. It is possible that he intended this stroke as a suspension stroke to abbreviate the end of the word (i.e. the -min portion of domin) but it cannot be said with certainty.

This word is formed out of a "g" with a suspension stroke and a lenition mark; it is not clear what form could be understood here that would require a lenited consonant other than "gho", perhaps modelled on prep. dha.

Black (0081020) takes this as Fuarnadhail, 'quarrelsome', derived from fuarnadh, 'controversy, argument'. While this makes sense in context, its interpretation as a compound of úar/fuar and náimdemail/náimdemail in this edition would not mean positing an otherwise unattested word. Furthermore, this particular run of adjectives also contains feimlaidar, another compound adjective where we see -ei- in feim representing the same sound as the -i- in nidhoil when it is understood as the word nàimhdeil. This bolsters the present understanding as a compound of fuar and náimdemail.

Alasdair mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair originally wrote 'soighdic' but a later ascender was added to the right hand side of the c to form a the letter d. A lenition dot was added in the same ink. As the ink used to make these two additions appears similar to ink used later in the manuscript it is likely that mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair was responsible for these emmendations.
Black (0071002) understood as a form of èasgach, unlike the present edition in which it is understood to be a form of inscnech/innsgineach, with the sense "sprightly, vigorous, lively".
Black (0020747) took this as the verb aom, unlike this edition in which it is understood to be the verb sream.

Black (0010284) took the first part of this word as tom, transcribing the piece of text in question as 'do thoumchromidir na toin' and giving a translation of 'backsides bent into the hillocks'. What Black takes as the letter m could be either an m or in when compared with the same in the surrounding text. Based on this, this transcription has understood the first part of this word to be a form of tón, 'bum', with the compound tónchromm being understood as a verb with the sense of 'squat'.
Black (0010112) suggests the headword riodhanach which is not attested in Dwelly or the DIL. In the present editon it is understood to be a form of the adjective frioghanach.

Black (0090575) gives the headword "greamaichte" for this. Although he gives the same meaning as is inteded with the postulated headword in this edition (grasping), greamaichte is another word in Gaelic with a different meaning.

Black (0080729) understood this to be a form of fód, with the phrase foud fola meaning 'clot', but I have not found a source for this in Dwelly or in DIL. The present editor postulates that foud fola could be 'a spurt of blood'.

Black (0060849) gives the headword darach for the second component of this compound. The present editor believes it to be the lemma daróc/darag. The palatalisation in the dative further suggests that this is a feminine noun, which fits with darag but not with darach.

Of brath Black (0030726) says that 'O'Rahilly's ed.[1962] has tuc urchur de uimpe for this phrase [and] I suspect this means something similar. Bráth must here be a part of the body, cf. Dwelly brá "brow"? - "He smashed him around it?"'. He then took throsda as a form of the preposition trasna (0010300). In this edition this is understound to be a triple compound from bráth, trost (cf. trostbéim) and buille, with the sense of ‘a deadly resounding blow’. This sense of bráth also appears later in this text.

This letters appears to be an s with a subsequent horizontal stroke from the descender of the s from left to right, the purpose of which is unclear to the present editor. Despite this extra horizontal stroke, this letter form does not resemble mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair's forms of the letter f. Comparison with O'Rahilly (1962): l.330, wherein the character in question appears as 'Sighmall ua Midir' supports the reading of a name beginning with s and the same charachter further appears as 'siodhmhall' later on this folio (p.12, l.19).
This character earlier appeared as 'Néamhinach' (p.12, l.13).
Suggested meaning of this verse: If Ilbrec and Tadg, his men, and Midir came, I tell them that they are welcome.

Black (0041081) took this as còmhradh. The letter after the bh appears to be an n and as such has been understood here as a form of cáemna referring to Badhbha's pleasure at seeing the fían in dire straits.
Black (0071001) took this to be a form of èasgach, unlike this edition in which it is understood to be a form of inscnech, cf. p. 1, l.1 of this text.
Black (0110317) gives this as narrannach. Have been unable to find a form of this in DIL/Dwelly/Teanglann, it has been postulated that it originates in the adj. forránach.
Black's note on the form gonin (0090509) appears to understand it as a conjugated form of the verb rather than a noun. In the present edition it is understood to be a noun.

It appears that mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair initially wrote a d with lenition dot and o. This was subsequently changed by the same to a form of go by adding a looped descender to the d to form a g, and possibly by creating a heavier and more vertical downstroke on the right-hand side of the o. An exact rendering thus gives the reader gho, although it is likely that the scribe intended it to be read as go due to the majority of other instances of this use of go appearing without a lenition marker.
O'Rahilly (1962): p.49 has cenn, not a from of corp here, which would appears to make more sense.
O'Rahilly's edition (1962),: p.50, has Cathair Claonratha, while Ó Siochfhrada's text has Cathair Connraoi.
Black (0110341) took this as neamh. In this edition it is understood to be a form ofnoíb.
Black (0010281) took this to be toll-cheannach, meaning 'hole-headed one'. Here it is understood to be a form of tálcendach from tálcend.

Black (0080709) appears to have missed the ur-abbreviation when transcribing this word, which caused subsequent uncertaintly due to the headword being noted as Foabh. The noun fáebar can be understood as both a sharp edge or a a sharp-bladed weapon, amongst other similar meaning.
Black (0020277) took this to be a form of aimhleas whereas in this edition it is understood to be a form of áilges.

This character later appears as fuinn (p.18, ll.3, 33 and p.19, l.2). Consequently when this person is represented as f and a suspension stroke the same spelling is used in the expansion. The spelling of this name has been emended here and in p.18, l.25 solely for consistency within this text.

This name appears on p.19, l.2 in verse. As the metre is deibhidhe we should have 'Cumáin' to rhyme with bháin in the previous line of the same verse. The rhyme as it appears in this MS, however, is faulty as line 1a ends with 'baine' (for báine) and 1b with the q (for cu) abbreviation which is used on a number of occasions prior to that to abbreviate the name in question here. That an earlier exemplar would have had Cumáin is supported by the name appearing as Dubháin in O'Rahilly (1962): p.54; Cubháin in the other versions of this tale (O'Rahilly 1962: p.89). For further appearances of the same character see O'Rahilly (1962): p.89. As mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair writes 'Cubinn' plene on p.18, l.9, and regularly writes 'cumin' with an n-stroke over the n therein it is clear that the name is thought to be Cum(ha)inn in this text and has not been emended in this instance. Further instances where an expansion is required employ the ending -inn.

A punctum appears over the i in ni. Due to the presence of the tittle in most modern fonts, this cannot be represented using the current transcription and editorial methods. Here the punctum is understood to be a lenition dot and has thus been moved to the f in faicimse.

In this word, the first letter of the second element has been changed by the scribe while writing. In this transcription it has been understood that a c was initially written and subsequently changed to an l. Black understood that the opposite had happened, with the scribe initially writing an l and then changing it to a c. He consequently notes the word as comhchobhradh (0041019), as opposed to labrad which is given as the headword in this edition.
Erna (with tall e) appears to be a misreading of Luachra.

This symbol is somewhat difficult to decipher. It closely resembles an Arabic number 6 but the use of the number or pronoun sé would not make sense here. If it is not a number 6 as an abbreviaiton, the present editor is of the opinion that the closest symbol it resembles is one of the forms of the ampersand as used in secretary hand.

note.p: Black (0010137) took this to be ruig. In the present transcription it is understood to be a form of rosaig, in the sense of 'comes to an end, is finished'.
Or tonn + muir?

Black (0020626) notes this as ana-tharraing, meaning 'a great heave'. In this edition it has been understood as 'the next heave', a construction which has been used earlier in the text when describing a skirmish between two warriors.

p.note: Or madh as both a suspension stroke a leniton dot are present?

note.p: Black (0090404) was unsure of this word and suggested a translation of 'a big slurp (?) of a laugh'. In the current edition it is taken to be a form of glothar. The variant gluthar appears in Dinneen.
The scribe changes both ink and pen here. The pen is sharper and the ink black in contrast to the brown ink used thusfar.
a from do ok here?

The da-abbreviation here is quite angular and ill-formed, resembling the allmara-abbreviaiton more than the da-abbreviation found thus far. The context and stroke to indicate a long vowel, however, mean that the scribe's intended symbol is unmistakable.
For this usage of alladh in Miscellaneous Vocabulary collected from Martin MacKinnon, Kilmuir, Skye.
Black (0040718) suggests an interpretation of this as 'mercy'. Is this the same as coicill, as noted here, or coicell, http://www.dil.ie/10052?
Black (0040868) notes this as a form of coireach and supplies a translation of 'why not'. In this edition it is understood as a form of cóir, meaning 'who should?'
Black (0120437) has a note on this under HW sgiamhach for sgea in text.
Black (0040744) suggests an interpretation of this as 'mercy'. Is this the same as coicill, as noted here, or coicell, http://www.dil.ie/10052?
Here Mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair initially writes the letter n and subsequently adds a downwards stroke that curces to the left to create the arabic number 9 abbreviation.
Black (0020668) has this as anlann, 'equivalent', hence 'the same as you'. I do not know what the HW is, however.

Unlike this edition, Black (0030183) understands this as a form ofbarr. In this edition it has been understood as a form of the preposition thar as forms with an initial f- appear elsewhere in the text.
Black (0010120) reads this and a superscript o, standing for mór. The present editor thinks it the letter form is that of a c and that this is a form of amach.
Black (0090197) notes this as gein, for duine. He's probably right but I thought g- for dh- and HW is dein. Change HW to duine or keep as dein?
Black (0040124) takes this as a noun, ceanna-bheart, whereas in this edition it is understood to be an adjective, cennbeartach

Black (0010356) gives this headword as gnáthasach. Here, it is understood to be a form of Early Gaelic gnáthach, Modern Gaelic gnàthach as mac Mhaighsdir Alasdair occasionally uses the s + suspension stroke abbreviation elsewhere in this MS to represent ch rather than cht.
Black (0061198) took this to the the genitive singular of the noun dìle. Here it is understood to be the adjective dílennda.

Black (0010208)gives this as taithbheothuighim but the HDSG headword is given as ath-bheothachadh. While the meaning of both is very close, the present editor is in agreement with Black and understands the first element of this compound to be from táth.
Black (0031131) takes cen as as a single word canas. Here it is understood to be two words, a form of the interrogative cía and the prepositional pronoun as.
Black has different readings for araon (0020933) and muirne (0010013).

Black understood the (non)compounding of this run of adjectives differently giving readings of cuislinn as part of caonchuislinn (0060689), dlùth standing alone (0070142), grinn standing alone (0010371), maismhéarach (0010083) (separate slip for méarach portion only: (0010093)
The b here is badly formed and resembles an l, something which also happens with the same word on p. 4, l.20.
Black (0010141) gives this as Rumaladh with a suggested menaing of 'drubbing'. Here it is postulated that it is *rothmolad, from rothmol.
Black understood this differently, noting neimhsgridolicht (HDSG: neo-sgreadalachd) (0010018) and sgreadalacht (0010167). Here it is understood to be neo-sgrìdealachd.
Black understood this as the adjective calma, and noted that it should be corrected to calmaide (0031103). In the present edition it is understood to be a form of the verb calmaigid.
For this usage of alladh in Miscellaneous Vocabulary collected from Martin MacKinnon, Kilmuir, Skye.

The text seems to have first contained only ag but the same hand, as evidenced by the same ink being used, returns to add the us-abbreviation and this is attached to the g that was originally written.
Black (0020490) was unsure of this word and suggested that beir áithib may be for for a bha air a thaobh. The present edition supposes a form of the Early Gaelic attach, meaning protection.

note.p: Black (0010156) takes this as sèimhneach, 'silent'. In the present transcription it is understood as seimnech, 'riveted'.
Black (0010193) takes this as suaimhneach, 'silent'. In the present edition it is understood to be súaimnech for súainmech, 'thonged (of spears)'.

Black (0071170) wonders whether this may be eiteach, meaning 'feathery' and thus idiomatically 'frequented by birds'. O'Rahilly (1962): l.1108, has aiteangharbh here. The present form cannot be matched with a known verion of gorse or furze but it therefore seems likely that the word in question is eitheach, meaning 'hill of oaks,'.
